body:
Previously we had just extracted the extension name from the field and discarded the rest of the metadata.  Unfortunately, these fields are used to parameterize extension types.  For example:

```
// A fixed shape tensor extension type for tensors with shape (2, 3)
metadata: {
    "ARROW:extension:name": "arrow.fixed_shape_tensor",
    "ARROW:extension:metadata": "{\"shape\":[2,3]}",
},
```

This PR keeps all of the metadata information.  This also allows for a lossless transformation when users have their own custom field metadata.

Once we support null values in all types, we can serialize a null struct as having all nulls for each of it's fields. This will avoid read amplification when reading validity of values within the struct, since whether a column in a struct is null is [determined by bitwise anding the struct's validity and the columns validity](https://arrow.apache.org/docs/format/Columnar.html#struct-layout). If we serialize such that they are the same, we don't have to load multiple validity values.

The trouble is when we read back, we would want to reconstruct the validity bitmap of the struct. We could do this based on the fields that are returned, though it might have some unexpected results. For example, if you inserted records:

```ndjson
{"x": {"a": 1, "b": "y"}}
{"x": null}
{"x": {"a": null, "b": "z"
```

and then queries with projection `x.a`, you would get:

```ndjson
{"x": {"a": 1}}
{"x": null}
{"x": null}
```

Since `x.a` is null for the last record, it would interpret `x` itself as being null (since it doesn't know about the value of `x.b`. This might be a fine tradeoff.
